  "why": "The paper enforces input validity and naturalness via standard Lp-norm validity constraints and a “conservative” per-mutation constraint (i.e., it constrains each applied transformation and uses conservative settings compared to prior work), and reports high manual validity rates. These measures show the authors enforce semantic consistency / naturalness at each mutation step. However, the method does not describe any mechanism that explicitly controls semantic similarity relative to the original seed across multiple GA iterations (e.g., tracking cumulative distortion or constraining distance to the original seed); mutations are applied iteratively to chromosomes in the population (mutating already-mutated inputs), so only per-step/conservative constraints are enforced rather than an explicit prevention of cumulative drift. Therefore the paper matches the “Medium” definition: semantic consistency and naturalness are enforced between successive mutation steps but the design does not account for accumulation of distortion across iterations.",
